<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0847-B"><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>&quot;The whole country will be witness to the discussions,&quot; Tekebayev said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>He was regarded as the most reformist and liberal of the ex-Soviet Central Asian leaders.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Akayev denied that, and blamed outside meddling for sparking protests in this nation of 5 million that resembled earlier actions in Ukraine and Georgia, which brought pro-Western opposition leaders to power.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Ukraine last year and Georgia in 2003 also saw mass protests that ushered the opposition into power, and both dispatched envoys to Kyrgyzstan last week to offer their help.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Akayev had previously refused to recognize Kurmanbek Bakiyev, a former opposition leader approved by both parliaments as interim president, saying he considered Tekebayev the country's legitimate political leader.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>But he also sought to maintain good ties with Russia.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>&quot;Akayev has made an important decision,&quot; Kyrgyz lawmaker Tashkul Kereksizov said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Parliamentary speaker Omurbek Tekebayev agreed with lawmakers Wednesday who called for Thursday's session to be broadcast live to this nation of 5 million and for representatives from all of Kyrgyzstan's political branches to be present.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Askar Akayev signed his resignation as Kyrgyzstan's president Monday, lawmakers said, 11 days after he fled the country amid a popular uprising that saw his offices stormed by protesters and parts of the Kyrgyz capital looted by mobs.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="15" sums="10,11,13,14,23,25,29,3,35,41,42,43,44,49,51"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/><scu uid="27" label="There was looting in Bishkek" weight="2"/><scu uid="38" label="Massive uprisings continued in Kyrgyzstan" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Prior to resigning, Akayev and members of the delegation on Sunday signed an agreement reaffirming that he would enjoy security guarantees granted to former leaders under the Kyrgyz law.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>By stepping down, he removes the last major obstruction to holding new presidential elections, which the interim government has tentatively scheduled for June 26.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>But Akayev drew international criticism for abuses in elections and began to take a tougher line with opponents.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="22" label="Akayev's government had cracked down on opposition groups" weight="1"/><scu uid="21" label="There was international criticism for election abuses" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Kyrgyzstan was the latest former Soviet country to be upended by popular protests.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="14,44"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>He fled his country late last month amid strong opposition protests.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev has verbally agreed to resign as president, the Interfax news agency quoted the Kyrgyz parliament speaker as saying Saturday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="10,22,25,32,36"><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>Tekebayev said upon arrival in Moscow, &quot;Our mission has been authorized by the parliament.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Some of his later Cabinet members were his former students and friends from his academic life.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Parliament will formally endorse Akayev's resignation Tuesday, he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Kereksizov said Akayev had recorded a statement to the nation, the tape of which would be played to a session of the Kyrgyz parliament on Tuesday and then broadcast on Kyrgyz television.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="3" sums="12,38,8"><scu uid="33" label="Akayev's recorded resignation was to be broadcast in Kyrgyzstan." weight="4"/><scu uid="32" label="Akayev's recorded resignation was to be presented to parliament." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>Akayev has &quot;a sober view&quot; on the situation in the country and, as head of state, &quot;he is fully aware of his actions and has acted in the people's interests,&quot; Tekebayev reportedly said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Akayev had hoped to give his farewell address in person, but anger against the longtime leader still runs high, and the new leadership warned that his return could spark further unrest and put his life in danger.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>Akayev's resignation would calm Kyrgyzstan's stormy political waters and allow the nation's focus to shift from the ouster to presidential elections in June.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Opponents worried that Akayev planned to seek a referendum on allowing him to run for another term, fears that intensified after the elections widely criticized by the West as unfair gave him a legislature overwhelmingly dominated by his supporters.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="21" label="There was international criticism for election abuses" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0098"><line>Kyrgyzstan's constitution requires the president to return to Kyrgyzstan and announce his resignation to all members of parliament.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>&quot;We have received the president's verbal agreement,&quot; Tekebayev told Agence France-Presse on Saturday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>The 60-year-old Akayev became leader of Kyrgyzstan in 1990, a year before it became independent in the collapse of the Soviet Union.</line><line>The storming of the presidential administration building was the culmination of weeks of protests by opposition supporters who accused Akayev of manipulating parliamentary elections earlier this year to give him a compliant legislature.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/><scu uid="1" label="On March 24, 2005 there were protests in Bishkek." weight="2"/><scu uid="38" label="Massive uprisings continued in Kyrgyzstan" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>Many accuse Akayev of corruption and obstruction of opposition political groups.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="20,32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>President Askar Akayev, once hailed for creating an island of democracy in former Soviet Central Asia, paid a heavy price for betraying the trust of his people, who swept him from office in a popular uprising last month.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="41,51"><scu uid="38" label="Massive uprisings continued in Kyrgyzstan" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>He graduated from the Leningrad Institute of Fine Mechanics and Optics in 1967 with an honors degree in math, engineering and computers and later received a doctorate from the Moscow Institute of Engineering and Physics.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>The resignation, witnessed by a Kyrgyz notary, needed to be presented to the 75-member parliament on Tuesday to become effective.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>They recognized the new parliament, whose election had set off the protest movement, with the caveat that the positions of some of the newly elected members would be revoked because of campaign and voting abuses.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Opponents complained that in recent years, however, that he showed authoritarian leanings and that opposition activity was repressed.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>In his address to the nation, Akayev &quot;listed the nation's achievements during his 14 1/2-year presidency, but also apologized to people who bore grudges against him,&quot; said Tekebayev's aide, Bermet Bukasheva.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Popular anger against what many saw as rigged parliamentary elections earlier this year fueled the revolt against Akayev, along with persistent poverty and widespread corruption.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Popular anger against what many saw as rigged parliamentary elections earlier this year fueled the revolt, as did crushing poverty and widespread corruption.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Kyrgyzstan was the latest former Soviet country to be upended by popular protests.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>There are high hopes among Kyrgyz democracy advocates that with national and international attention so focused on the election, the voting could finally establish Kyrgyzstan as a truly democratic state.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>We want to create a new tradition for Kyrgyzstan, to lay the basis for clean, honest elections,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>&quot;Had he not left the country to chaos, then we could have considered accepting his resignation.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>When the end finally came, popular resentment against Akayev was so high that he chose to tape a farewell address to the nation, rather than return to give it live.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>In his address to the nation, Akayev &quot;listed the nation's achievements during his 14 1/2-year presidency, but also apologized to people who bore grudges against him,&quot; said Tekebayev's aide, Bermet Bukasheva.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>After the Sept. 11, 2001, terrorist attacks, Akayev became a Washington ally by allowing U.S.-led troops and planes to use Kyrgyzstan's main airport for combat operations against the Taliban regime in nearby Afghanistan.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>&quot;Akayev said that he wouldn't struggle against the new government, and that amounted to his recognition of the new Kyrgyzstan authorities,&quot; Kereksizov said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>He was criticized for failing to bring officials responsible for the deaths to justice.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>But Kereksizov said it was still too early for him to return.</line><line>The 60-year-old Akayev became leader of Kyrgyzstan in 1990, a year before it became independent in the collapse of the Soviet Union.</line><line>Akayev fled, deepening his country's political crisis, as the previous and newly elected parliaments competed for legitimacy.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>Akayev, who fled to Russia amid opposition protests last week, suggested in a Russian television interview Tuesday that he might be willing to submit a formal resignation if his security is guaranteed by the new Kyrgyz parliament.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="10,42"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="11" label="Akayev said he would resign if promised safety." weight="1"/><scu uid="38" label="Massive uprisings continued in Kyrgyzstan" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>The parliament elected in that vote was allowed to keep its seats despite Akayev's ouster, and it named one of the ousted president's longtime foes, Tekebayev, as speaker.</line><line>An 18-minute farewell address recorded by Akayev in Moscow was to be played at the session.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>Parliament speaker Omurbek Tekebayev, who heads the delegation, said Akayev had given a verbal agreement that he would resign, 10 days after protesters stormed the presidential administration building.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="37,6"><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>The resignation _ to be effective Tuesday _ was signed at the Kyrgyz Embassy in Moscow a day after Akayev met with a delegation representing Kyrgyzstan's interim leadership, headed by parliament speaker Omurbek Tekebayev.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="3,33,35,43"><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/><scu uid="13" label="Akayev and the parliamentary delegation held three hours of talks" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>The talks were then joined by other members of the Kyrgyz delegation.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Kyrgyz officials had pushed hard to secure Akayev's resignation, seeing it as a significant step toward restoring political order and giving a stamp of legitimacy to the new leadership, which rose to power amid widespread looting and chaos.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Akayev, 60, became president of Kyrgyzstan in 1991 in the dying months of the Soviet Union _ unusual for a former academic in a region largely run by career Communist bureaucrats who cultivated absolute power.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>A delegation of Kyrgyz legislators will travel to Moscow on Sunday to negotiate final terms of the resignation, according to the speaker of the country's new parliament, Omurbek Tekebayev.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>&quot;All privileges will be guaranteed to him according to the law&quot; if he resigns voluntarily, Tekebayev said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>The signing of the resignation document came after nearly three hours of talks between Akayev and the Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation, which arrived here earlier in the day.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Some officials are angry that Akayev is being allowed to resign rather than face impeachment.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>&quot;We think that the voluntary handover of power will create a new political situation in Kyrgyzstan.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Demonstrators stormed and ransacked the presidential administration building, sending the president and his family fleeing.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>The political chaos began to ebb last week after the previous parliament ceded authority.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>Akayev fled his country on March 24 when opposition supporters stormed the main government building in Bishkek and has since hinted he wants to return and might resign if his security is guaranteed.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0098"><line>A delegation from the parliament of Kyrgyzstan will leave the capital Bishkek Saturday night for Moscow to negotiate with the country's ousted president Askar Akayev on his resignation, the parliamentary press office said Saturday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="11,14,23,41,44,49"><scu uid="12" label="A Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation went to Moscow." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>Kyrgyzstan's exiled president, Askar Akayev, has agreed in principle to step down, Kyrgyz officials said Saturday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="25,29,37,43,57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>&quot;Akayev has made an important decision,&quot; Kyrgyz lawmaker Tashkul Kereksizov said Monday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0098"><line>The opposition claimed Akayev rigged recent parliamentary polls to pave the way for winning a further presidential term later this year.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="20,5,51"><scu uid="39" label="The rigged parliamentary elections caused anger." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>By stepping down, he removes the last major obstruction to holding new presidential elections, which the interim government has tentatively scheduled for June 26.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>A day earlier, Akayev verbally agreed to relinquish power, a decision by a man described by Tekebayev as having &quot;a sober view&quot; on the situation in the country.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Kyrgyzstan was the latest former Soviet republic to be upended by popular protests.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="14,44"/></line><line>Parliament was forced to adjourn Tuesday without formally accepting the ousted leader's resignation because lawmakers failed to muster a quorum, adding to the confusion gripping this ex-Soviet republic since March 24 when Akayev fled to Russia amid mass protests.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,19"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Lawmakers gathered Tuesday to hear ousted President Askar Akayev's farewell address and accept his resignation, almost two weeks after he fled Kyrgyzstan as opposition-led protesters stormed his office and toppled his government.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="3" sums="29,55,6"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="32" label="Akayev's recorded resignation was to be presented to parliament." weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>A parliamentary delegation traveled to Moscow to persuade Akayev to sign a formal resignation, which lawmakers were expected to vote on Tuesday.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>The talks proceeded in a constructive manner and demonstrated our full mutual understanding,&quot; Akayev told a press conference in the embassy after the talks.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>The 60-year-old Akayev became leader of Kyrgyzstan in 1990, a year before it became independent in the collapse of the Soviet Union.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Although he effectively ceased being Kyrgyzstan's leader after fleeing the country ahead of demonstrators who stormed his office, Akayev's stubborn refusal to formally resign cast a shadow over the legitimacy of the nation's new leadership.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>Akayev fled the Kyrgyz capital on March 24 as mass protests outside the presidential compound turned violent.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Akayev surfaced in Russia several days later.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>In 1989, he was elected a representative for southern Kyrgyzstan at the Soviet Union's Supreme Council, where he was considered one of the liberal deputies and had close ties to Gorbachev.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Fifty-five legislators present in the 75-seat Jogorku Kenesh Wednesday voted almost unanimously to endorse the decision.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>Akayev has demanded that in return for his resignation he be allowed to address the parliament and the nation.</line><line>But Kyrgyzstan's new government is reluctant to give him such a platform, fearing it could incite new unrest.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0098"><line>Earlier in the day, the chairwomen of the Kyrgyz Constitutional Court Cholpon Bayekova raised the possibility of Akayev's resigning abroad by saying that representatives of the parliament could go to Russia to collect and return with his resignation documents.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Askar Akayev signed his resignation as Kyrgyzstan's president, lawmakers said, 11 days after he fled the country amid a popular uprising in which his offices were stormed by protesters and parts of the Kyrgyz capital looted by mobs.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="15" sums="10,11,13,14,23,25,29,3,35,41,42,43,44,49,51"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/><scu uid="27" label="There was looting in Bishkek" weight="2"/><scu uid="38" label="Massive uprisings continued in Kyrgyzstan" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>&quot;We hope to return tonight with his resignation.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>He was the only candidate in the 1991 presidential election, held less than two months after the Kyrgyz parliament declared independence from the Soviet Union.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>There were two nights of looting and gunfire in the capital, in which at least three people were killed.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Kyrgyzstan was the latest former Soviet country to be upended by popular protests.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>&quot;He said he will not confront the new government in either words or deeds and wished it success.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>We've arrived here with a notary who will document Akayev's resignation.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>Akayev's resignation would likely be a significant step toward solidifying a sense of political order in the country following last month's chaos.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>Akayev, Kyrgyz president for the past 14 years, fled his country last Thursday when opposition supporters stormed the main government building in Bishkek.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="13" sums="13,14,19,20,21,32,36,37,43,44,47,48,49"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>During his first years of his presidency, Kyrgyzstan acquired the image of an island of democracy in a region noted for heavy-handed autocratic leadership.</line><line>The resignation is likely to be a significant step toward restoring political order to Kyrgyzstan, which plunged into uncertainty March 24 when an anti-Akayev demonstration exploded into a clash outside the presidential administration.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>He was regarded as the most reformist and liberal of the ex-Soviet Central Asian leaders.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>&quot;I think it's a truly historic mission,&quot; Tekebayev said on the flight from the Kyrgyz capital Bishkek.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Parliament will formally endorse Akayev's resignation Tuesday, he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>On Monday, he ended that uncertainty at the Kyrgyz Embassy in Moscow by signing a resignation agreement ending his 14-year reign.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>However, as Kyrgyz Foreign Minister Roza Otunbayeva has warned Akayev would be in danger if he returns to Kyrgyzstan, Constitutional Court Chairwoman Cholpon Bayekova said it would also be acceptable for a Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation to meet Akayev outside the country and bring his notarized resignation to Bishkek.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="2" sums="16,22"><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/><scu uid="12" label="A Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation went to Moscow." weight="2"/><scu uid="29" label="Akayev's safety could not be guaranteed" weight="1"/><scu uid="41" label="The Kyrgyz constitution requires a president to present his resignation in person to parliament" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>In his address to the nation, Akayev &quot;listed the nation's achievements during his 14 1/2-year presidency, but also apologized to people who bore grudges against him,&quot; said Tekebayev's aide, Bermet Bukasheva.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>&quot;We have just finished talks with the Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation led by (parliament speaker) Omurbek Tekebayev.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="13,37"><scu uid="44" label="The new speaker of Parliament headed the delegation." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Akayev was re-elected in 1995 and 2000 in internationally criticized votes.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>Ousted Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev said Sunday he has signed the document on his resignation in the Kyrgyz Embassy in Moscow.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="8" sums="11,12,13,16,25,32,36,6"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>&quot;A verbal agreement has been received from the president that he will relinquish power,&quot; said Omurbek Tekebayev, speaker of the newly-inaugurated parliament elected in the disputed polls in February and March.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="55"><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>But Kereksizov said Monday that Akayev recognized the new authorities.</line><line>&quot;He said he will not confront the new government in either words or deeds and wished it success.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>The negotiations resulted in a four-section document, one of which said, &quot;the president of Kyrgyzstan announces his early resignation in compliance with his own statement,&quot; Akayev said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>&quot;He voiced hope that the forthcoming presidential election will be democratic and fully transparent.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>The message was to be broadcast on state television later Tuesday to the rest of this former Soviet republic of 5 million people.</line><line>The interim authorities have scheduled a new presidential election for June 26, but many feared its legitimacy would be undermined if Akayev clung to the presidency _ even in forced exile.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Born Nov. 10, 1944, in the northern village of Kyzyl-Bayrak, Akayev grew up in a family of collective farmers.</line><line>He invited the Kremlin to set up an air base just 30 kilometers (18 miles) from the U.S. base, saying Kyrgyzstan would be &quot;a land for cooperation between Russia and the United States.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>However, Tekebayev suggested Sunday that a near-future return for Akayev would be inappropriate because of anger among the populace against him.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Akayev resurfaced in Russia several days later.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>Many senior Kyrgyz politicians have announced their intent to run.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>Akayev, Kyrgyzstan's president for the past 14 years, was accused of rigging the recent parliamentary polls to pave the way for winning a further presidential term later this year.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="20,51"><scu uid="39" label="The rigged parliamentary elections caused anger." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Akayev, 60, became leader of Kyrgyzstan in 1990, a year before it gained independence in the collapse of the Soviet Union.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Most Kyrgyz reject those criticisms, but express fears that Akayev's overthrow won't lead to real change.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>Akayev is expected to sign a resignation document in Moscow, Tekebayev said, adding that the resignation ceremony in Moscow will be attended by a state notary and the press.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>The resignation _ to be effective Tuesday _ was signed at the Kyrgyz Embassy in Moscow a day after Akayev met with a delegation representing Kyrgyzstan's interim leadership, headed by parliament speaker Omurbek Tekebayev.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Lawmakers also planned to watch an 18-minute taped message from Akayev.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Corruption has also grown, with business leaders accusing Akayev's family of grabbing control over profitable enterprises, and rigging deals to line their pockets.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0098"><line>Akayev, who fled the country amid strong opposition protests last week, has hinted that he wants to return and might resign if his security is guaranteed.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="11" label="Akayev said he would resign if promised safety." weight="1"/><scu uid="20" label="Opposition against Akayev strengthened" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>&quot;He will return some day to his native country, but he'd better stay in Russia for now,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Some observers blamed Tuesday's confusion to a lack of discipline and disorder typical of a new parliament settling into its job.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>He said that if negotiations failed, the parliament would start impeachment proceedings.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Kyrgyzstan's parliament has decided to hold a special session on Thursday to accept the resignation of exiled President Askar Akayev, which will help the Central Asian nation leave behind its recent political turmoil.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="0,29"><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>&quot;The people needed it very much.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Although the newly elected legislature has been seen as dominated by Akayev supporters, it nominated Tekebayev, an Akayev opponent, as parliament speaker.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>During his first years of his presidency, Kyrgyzstan acquired the image of an island of democracy in a region noted for heavy-handed autocratic leadership.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>Akayev was elected president by the Soviet Kyrgyz parliament in 1990, and was credited with calming ethnic tensions in southern Kyrgyzstan that year after clashes between Kyrgyz and Uzbeks killed dozens of people.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="12,36,38,42"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>&quot;The majority of people do not support our actions; they want immediate revenge,&quot; Tekebayev said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>But Kereksizov said Monday that Akayev recognized the new authorities.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="16"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>The resignation is likely to be a significant step toward restoring political order to Kyrgyzstan, which plunged into uncertainty March 24 when an anti-Akayev demonstration exploded into a clash outside the presidential administration.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0098"><line>The delegation, headed by Parliament Speaker Omurbek Tekebayev, will negotiate with Akayev, now in Moscow, on details concerning his resignation, the office said in a statement.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>&quot;The revolution has taken place, the new government is working, but this document is necessary to bring the developments into the legal field,&quot; Kereksizov said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>But Keriksizov said it was still too early for him to return.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>The storming of the presidential administration building was the culmination of weeks of protests by opposition supporters who accused Akayev of manipulating parliamentary elections earlier this year to give him a compliant legislature.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>&quot;The people needed it very much.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Akayev surfaced in Russia several days later.</line><line>Although the newly elected legislature has been seen as dominated by Akayev supporters, it nominated Tekebayev, an Akayev opponent, as parliament speaker.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>As head of state, &quot;he is fully aware of his actions and has acted in the people's interests,&quot; Tekebayev said Saturday.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>There were two nights of looting and gunfire in the capital, in which at least three people were killed.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>Akayev's verbal consent to step down came shortly after the chairwoman of the Kyrgyz Constitutional Court, Cholpon Bayekova, said Saturday that Akayev is ready to put his resignation in writing.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>A delegation of Kyrgyzstan officials arrived in Moscow on Sunday for talks with ousted President Askar Akayev that they hope will lead to his formal resignation.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="5" sums="21,23,33,37,40"><scu uid="12" label="A Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation went to Moscow." weight="2"/><scu uid="13" label="Akayev and the parliamentary delegation held three hours of talks" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>&quot;He deserted the country and the people,&quot; said acting Prosecutor General Azimbek Beknazarov.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>When Akayev's son and daughter won parliamentary seats this year, fears rose that the family was becoming all-powerful.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Before the revolt, Akayev's term was set to expire after new elections in October.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Authorities have scheduled new presidential elections for June 26.</line><line>Mass protests ushered the opposition into power in Ukraine last year and Georgia in 2003.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>&quot;He voiced hope that the forthcoming presidential election will be democratic and fully transparent.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>He rejected the criticism, saying that &quot;Western standards (of democracy) can only be applied to the Western world.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>&quot;The revolution has taken place, the new government is working, but this document is necessary to bring the developments into the legal field,&quot; Kereksizov said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Interim president Kurmanbek Bakiyev and the heads of the Supreme and Constitutional Courts have also been invited to attend the event.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="29,55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Ukraine last year and Georgia in 2003 also saw popular uprisings force out entrenched leaders and bring to power reformers.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>&quot;He voiced hope that the forthcoming presidential election will be democratic and fully transparent.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>But the leaders who quickly filled the vacuum Akayev left behind have struggled to establish their legitimacy in the absence of his formal resignation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Tekebayev, who led the delegation to Moscow, acknowledged Tuesday that the delay meant Akayev continued formally to hold onto power _ albeit in exile.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="44" label="The new speaker of Parliament headed the delegation." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Akayev had previously refused to recognize Kurmanbek Bakiyev, a former opposition leader approved by both parliaments as interim president, saying he considered Tekebayev the country's legitimate political leader.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Prior to resigning, Akayev and members of the delegation on Sunday signed an agreement reaffirming that he would enjoy security guarantees granted to former leaders under the Kyrgyz law.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>An ally of reformist Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev, Akayev held out the promise of democracy and for a while, Kyrgyzstan was notable in the region for its relatively open politics.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>The president, as Kyrgyzstan's constitution stipulates, must address a parliament session in person to announce his resignation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Ukraine last year and Georgia in 2003 also saw popular uprisings force out entrenched leaders and bring reformers to power.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0098"><line>Akayev, Kyrgyz president for the past 14 years, fled his country on March 24 when opposition supporters stormed the main government building in Bishkek.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="13" sums="13,14,19,20,21,32,36,37,43,44,47,48,49"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Demonstrators broke into a main government building" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>A parliament member confirmed Tekebayev's statement.</line><line>Demonstrators broke through a security cordon around the building and damaged the inside, beating several senior officials severely.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>Kyrgyz officials pushed hard to secure Akayev's resignation, seen as a significant step toward restoring political order and giving a stamp of legitimacy to new leaders.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Riot police guarding the building fled, and protesters rushed inside.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>He was regarded as the most reformist and liberal of the ex-Soviet Central Asian leaders, but his increasing intolerance of dissent and his family's growing wealth turned public opinion against him.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>His term was due to expire in October.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>The Parliament called for new presidential elections on June 26, but none of the government's actions have been constitutional because Akayev remains the legal head of state until his mandate ends in October.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>&quot;Akayev said that he wouldn't struggle against the new government, and that amounted to his recognition of the new Kyrgyzstan authorities,&quot; Kereksizov said.</line><line>Riot police guarding the building fled, and protesters rushed inside.</line><line>&quot;He will return some day to his native country, but he'd better stay in Russia for now,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>However, he said, Akayev's resignation would ease conditions in the country.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Akayev, currently in exile in Russia, signed his formal resignation at the Kyrgyz Embassy in Moscow on Monday after talks with a parliamentary delegation led by Speaker Omurbek Tekebayev.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="14" label="Akayev signed a resignation document" weight="4"/><scu uid="13" label="Akayev and the parliamentary delegation held three hours of talks" weight="1"/><scu uid="44" label="The new speaker of Parliament headed the delegation." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>The interim authorities have tentatively scheduled a new presidential election for late June, but if Akayev were not to step down, the legitimacy of that election could be called into question.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>His image tarnished severely in 2002 when police killed six peaceful demonstrators in southern Kyrgyzstan and the government cracked down on opposition groups and independent media.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>Akayev, who arrived in the embassy shortly after at 3 p.m. local time (1100 GMT), first held a one-hour talk with Tekebayev.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Akayev fled, deepening his country's political crisis, as the previous and newly elected parliaments competed for legitimacy.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="7" label="Akayev fled the country for Russia." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>Akayev fled to Russia after the storming, leaving the country in control of an interim government.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050403.0121"><line>The resignation ceremony will be held on Monday, he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0009"><line>He began teaching in 1977 at the Polytechnic Institute in Frunze, as the Kyrgyz capital was then known.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050402.0075"><line>His resignation would pave the way for the opposition government that ousted him more than a week ago to recover its constitutional footing.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0007"><line>Kereksizov said Akayev had recorded a statement to the nation, the tape of which would be played to a session of the Kyrgyz parliament on Tuesday and then broadcast on Kyrgyz television.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>Kyrgyzstan's interim authorities have said the law providing immunity to Akayev as president would be observed and that Akayev would not be persecuted if he returned to the ex-Soviet Central Asian state.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050405.0127"><line>Akayev was ousted March 24 when a wave of protests that had seized southern Kyrgyzstan spread north to the capital.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>The political chaos began to ebb last week after the previous parliament ceded authority.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050403.0116"><line>A meeting with Akayev was to be held in the Kyrgyz Embassy, Tekebayev said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="16,57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050404.0816"><line>Opponents complained that in recent years, however, that he showed authoritarian leanings and that opposition activity was repressed.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="22" label="Akayev's government had cracked down on opposition groups" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>&quot;If he refuses to resign, it will be necessary to initiate an impeachment process, and in this case the president may be deprived of any guarantees,&quot; the speaker added.</line><line>A Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation headed by Tekebayev will leave Saturday evening for Moscow to discuss with Akayev the details of his resignation, the Kyrgyz parliament press service said.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="22,6"><scu uid="12" label="A Kyrgyz parliamentary delegation went to Moscow." weight="2"/><scu uid="44" label="The new speaker of Parliament headed the delegation." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050406.0066"><line>But parliament fell two short of its 50-person quorum.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20050402.0070"><line>The opposition accused the president of rigging the parliamentary vote to pave the way for winning a further presidential term later this year.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="20,51"><scu uid="39" label="The rigged parliamentary elections caused anger." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document></collection>